References

Statistics with R


Verzani, J. (2014). Using R for introductory statistics. CRC Press.


Introductory Statistics with R. Peter Dalgaard walks through the major statistical methods in R. UVic Library has an ecopy


A handbook of statistical analyses using R. UVic Library has an ecopy


Introductory Statistics for the Health Sciences covers an undergraduate statistics course and offers a collection of templates for visualizing basic statistical tests in R. See their GitHub repository for scripts and graph examples.

R

Venables, W. N., Smith, D. M., & R Development Core Team. (2002). An introduction to R.


Data Manipulation with R. UVic Library has an ecopy

Methods


Introduction to Statistical Learning free text, slides, and videos online. UVic Library has a hardcopy


Designing Experiments and Analyzing Data the book has a website with scripts used in the text, datasets are on the CD that comes with the book. Uvic Library has a hardcopy


Data Analysis Using Regression and Multilevel/Hierarchical Models. Uvic Library has a hardcopy


Experimental and Quasi-Experimental Designs for Generalized Causal Inference by Shadish, Cook, and Campbell . UVic Library has a hardcopy

Graphics


R Cookbook by Winston Chang is a perfect book to get you started with producing graphs with RStudio


Murrell, P. (2011). R graphics. CRC Press.

Papers

  • Jones, L. V., & Tukey, J. W. (2000). A sensible formulation of the significance test. Psychological methods, 5(4), 411.

  • Mook, D. G. (1983). In defense of external invalidity. American psychologist, 38(4), 379.

  • Rodgers, J. L. (2010). The epistemology of mathematical and statistical modeling: a quiet methodological revolution. American Psychologist, 65(1), 1.

  • Wickham, H. (2014). Tidy Data. Journal of Statistical SOftware, 59(10).

Meta resources

  • Resources Opinions Will Beasley gives brief reviews of key books and resources
  • CRAN books on R
